  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "The standard deviation measures how spread out a collection of values is from its mean. It answers the question: on average, how far do individual observations fall from the center? A standard deviation of 0 means every value is identical — there is no spread at all. A small standard deviation means values cluster tightly around the mean. A large standard deviation means values are widely dispersed.\nConsider two classes of students who both average 80 on a test. In one class, every student scores between 75 and 85 — the standard deviation is small (around 3). In the other, scores range from 40 to 100 — the standard deviation is large (around 20). The mean tells you the center; the standard deviation tells you how much the data scatter around that center.\n",
  "name": "Standard Deviation",
